\begin_layout Subsection
NMC Health
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A typical example: B.R Shetty's NMC Health (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

he likes to wear medals
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and has a website with his philosophy).
 The story didn't end well for him, as NMC's stock was delisted, bond traded
 at 7c on the dollar and the company eventually became bankrupt.
 B.R Shetty now hides in India.
 There were many red flags in this case: too good margins, unusually high
 cash, lack of board independence and family members in key financial positions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Margin analysis is a very important part of the job: it is extremely difficult
 to have margins around 10%-20%.
 NMC were borrowing significant amount of money from unusual sources (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

supply chain financing
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 Abnormally high costs (compared to similar firms) on the I/S might give
 a clue.
 In NMC Health case, family members were found to be involved.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As NMC Health was a big client for J.P Morgan, analysts refused to believe
 that the scam was true.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
GSX
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another example is GSX.
 A U.S company which became public in 2019.
 The company provides online courses for Chinese students of ages 6-16.
 Education is highly priced in China and people spend a significant portion
 of their income on it, which tells a very good story and provides an advantage
 over competitors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The problem with it is that most of the students are bots.
 Server farms were identified by large groups of students logging out from
 one course and logging in to another one at the same time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
GSX was one of the rare cases when people 
