\begin_layout Subsection
Factor Models
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Price restrictions in the APT come from the 
\series bold
absence of arbitrage
\series default
 (no security with negative price and non-negative payoff).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
factor model
\series default
 specifies how the security returns move with economic factors:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{r_{i}}-E(\tilde{r}_{i})=b_{i,1}\tilde{f}_{1}+\cdots+b_{i,K}\tilde{f}_{K}+\tilde{e}_{i}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}$
\end_inset

's are common factors for all securities (economic growth, interest rates,
 inflation, etc).
 For each factor, 
\begin_inset Formula $E(\tilde{f}_{i})=0$
\end_inset

 i.e only the 
\series bold
deviation
\series default
 is measured.
 In addition, zero covariance is often assumed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i,j}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\series bold
loading
\series default
 of the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

'th asset on the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

'th factor (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sensitivity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{e}_{i}$
\end_inset

 denotes the 
\series bold
idiosyncratic risk
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The APT provides a 
\series bold
theoretical
\series default
 justification for the empirical factor models which determine the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fair
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 rate of return.
 A diversified portfolio in this context is one that carries 
\series bold
no idiosyncratic risk
\series default
:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{r}_{p}-E(\tilde{r}_{p})=b_{p,1}\tilde{f}_{1}+\cdots+b_{p,K}\tilde{f}_{K}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The pricing equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E(\tilde{r}_{i})=\lambda_{0}+\lambda_{1}b_{i,1}+\cdots+\lambda_{K}b_{i,K}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
specifies a linear relation between the return of a security and its factor
 loadings.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

's are 
\series bold
factor risk premia
\series default
.
 For the risk-free asset: 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}=r_{f}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An 
\series bold
arbitrage
\series default
 arises when the risk is priced 
\series bold
inconsistently
\series default
 across (well-diversified) securities, e.g two securities can be found, which
 bear the 
\series bold
same
\series default
 risk/factor-loadings, but have 
\series bold
different
\series default
 discount rates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The APT is an alternative model to the CAPM, with fewer assumptions and
 weaker predictions.
\end_layout

